# UI Design Rule

## Goal

Generate UI that preserves the intended mood of the reference set while clearly avoiding direct reconstruction of any single source page.

## Required Process

1. Read the design system before drafting UI.
2. Prefer semantic tokens over hard-coded values.
3. Reuse existing components and patterns before inventing new ones.
4. Explain how the new layout differs from the reference sources.

## Hard Constraints

- Do not recreate a reference page section-by-section.
- Do not reuse distinct brand copy, iconography, illustration style, or visual motifs from the source sites.
- Change at least 3 of the following when generating a new page:
  - grid
  - proportions
  - whitespace rhythm
  - corner treatment
  - border strategy
  - shadow strategy
- Avoid generic AI landing-page tropes unless the design system explicitly calls for them.

## Visual Quality Rules

- Establish hierarchy through spacing and typography before adding visual decoration.
- Use one dominant accent and keep the rest restrained.
- Prefer strong section-level composition over noisy micro-styling.
- Avoid purple-on-white defaults, overused glassmorphism, and heavy gradients unless requested.

## Output Checklist

Before finalizing a UI proposal, confirm:

- Which semantic tokens are used
- Which components are reused
- Which pattern each section follows
- Which deliberate changes make the result original
